{"conflict_recognized": 0, "processed_response": "IBM's 1956 chess program was a groundbreaking achievement in the early days of artificial intelligence, marking a significant step in the development of computational thinking. Developed by Alex Bernstein and his team, it was one of the first attempts to program a computer to play chess, operating on the IBM 704. While its gameplay was rudimentary by modern standards, the program demonstrated the potential of computers to tackle complex logic-based problems. Its ability to analyze two half-move ply—a remarkably modest depth—highlighted both the limitations and ambition of early AI research.

